Credit Card Customer Segmentation for AllLife Bank

Data Analysis and Modeling by: Varun Kulkarni (kulkarnivarun@outlook.com)

Objective:¶

To identify different segments in the existing customer based on their spending patterns as well as past interaction with the bank.

Data Source¶

Credit Card Customer Data.xlsx

Tasks¶

  • Exploratory Data Analysis
  • K-Means Clustering
  • Hierarchical Clustering
  • Silhouette Scores for K-Means and Hierarchical Clustering
  • Comparison Between K-Means and Hierarchical Clusters
  • Analyzing Clusters - Finding Answers to Key Questions

Observations with EDA:¶

  • All attributes are numerical.
  • avg_credit_limit: This attribute indicates the average credit card limits of the customers. Most of the data values are between 10000 to 50000. The mean is higher then the 50th percentile value and is considerably right skewed. There are considerable outliers which should be treated.
  • total_credit_cards: This attribute indicates the total number of credit cards owned by a customer. The distribution seems quite normal with about 5 groups for values. The mean and 50 percentile value have little difference. There is little skewness observed here.
  • total_visits_bank: These are visits to the bank by the customers in person. The distribution seems fairly normal. There seems to be three peaks in the distribution, indicating three groups. The skewness level is fairly low.
  • total_visits_online: Assuming these are the requests for online banking. The distribution is quite skewed, with majority of the values between 0 and 5. There are some outliers observed, with which can work.
  • total_calls_made: This attribute indicates total number of support calls made by a customer. The distribution seems fairly normal. The two peaks indicate two majority groups of values in the data. Some skewness in the data is observed.
  • Based on the peaks in the distributions of these attributes, it seems 3 to 5 clusters should be good to get good segmentation across the customer data. Let's see.

Observations on data scaling, correlation and pair plots:¶

  • Applying zcore to data tells how many standard deviations far a data point is from the mean and unifies their scale. This will be very important for clustering as the algorithms depend on the distance between data points, and will not be dominated by any single attribute because of its scale.

  • There is good positive correlation between average_credit_limit and total_credit_cards. These attributes together may help determine a segment of customers.

  • Also there is good negative correlation between total_credit_cards and total_calls_made. These attributes may lie in different segments.

  • There is negative correlation between total_visits_online and total_visits_bank. These attributes may also help determine different segments of customers.

  • Based on the peaks observed in the plot along the diagonal, 3, 4 or 5 clusters should be good to get good segmentation across the data provided.

# Before we proceed, let's have a utility function to print the results from clustering algorithms, 
# like number of records in a cluster, Q1, median and Q3 quartiles per cluster, etc.

# Note: credit_df is the original data and scaled_df is the scaled data.

# Store Silhouette score for later comaprison
silhouette_score_map = {}

def get_clustering_results(algo='kmeans', num_clusters=3, linkage_method='average', dendrogram_dist=3.25, 
                           dist_metric='euclidean', show_box_plots=True):
    ''' Method to get clustering results
        algo            - Clustering algorithm: kmeans or hierarchical
        num_clusters    - Number of clsuters for kmeans clustering
        linkage_method  - Linkage method for hierarchical clustering
        dendrogram_dist - Dendrogramic distance to get certain number of clusters for hierarchical clustering
        dist_metric     - Distance metric for hierarchical clustering
        show_box_plots  - Indicator for showing box plots. Draw them if True.
    '''
    silhoutte_score = None
    cluster_labels = None
    silhouette_score_key = algo
    
    if algo == 'kmeans':
        # Get cluster labels using KMeans clustering
        kmeans_model = KMeans(random_state=SEED, n_clusters=num_clusters)
        cluster_labels = kmeans_model.fit_predict(scaled_df)
        silhouette_score_key += " " + str(num_clusters) + " Clusters"
        print("K-means clustering results for {0} clusters:".format(num_clusters))
        
    elif algo == 'hierarchical':
        # Get cluster labels using hierarchical clustering
        Z = linkage(scaled_df, metric=dist_metric, method=linkage_method, optimal_ordering=True)
        cluster_labels = fcluster(Z, t=dendrogram_dist, criterion='distance')
        clusters = max(cluster_labels)
        silhouette_score_key += " " + linkage_method.upper() + " with " + str(clusters) + " Clusters"
        print("Hierarchical clustering results for {0} linkage method with {1} clusters:".
              format(linkage_method, clusters))
        
    else:
        print("Incorrect clustering algorithm!")
        return
    
    # Print silhouette score
    silhoutte_score = round(silhouette_score(scaled_df, cluster_labels), 3)
    print('Silhouette Score: ', silhoutte_score)
    
    # Update silhouette score map
    silhouette_score_map[silhouette_score_key] = silhoutte_score
    
    # Get counts, Q1, median and Q3 quartiles, per cluster
    credit_df['Cluster'] = cluster_labels
    counts_df = credit_df.groupby('Cluster').count().sort_index()
    q1_df     = credit_df.groupby('Cluster').quantile(0.25).round(2).sort_index()
    median_df = credit_df.groupby('Cluster').median().round(2).sort_index()
    q3_df     = credit_df.groupby('Cluster').quantile(0.75).round(2).sort_index()
    
    # Create data frames for results
    summary_dict = {}
    for col in scaled_df.columns.to_list():
        summary_dict[col] = list(zip(q1_df[col].values, median_df[col].values, q3_df[col].values))    
    summary_df = pd.DataFrame(summary_dict, index=median_df.index)
    counts_df.index.name = 'Counts per cluster'    
    summary_df.index.name = '(Q1, Median, Q3) per cluster'
    
    # Display data frames
    disp.display(counts_df)
    disp.display(summary_df)
    
    # If indicated, draw box plots for clusters using scaled data
    if show_box_plots:
        scaled_copy = scaled_df.copy(deep=True)
        scaled_copy['Cluster'] = cluster_labels
        scaled_copy.boxplot(by='Cluster', layout=(2,3), figsize=(18,10));

K-Means Clustering ¶

Now, we will use K-Means clustering to group data based on their attribute. First, we need to determine the optimal number of groups. For that we conduct the knee test (elbow plot) to see where the knee happens.

In [13]:
# Let's consider 2 to 15 clusters for the knee test
clusters=range(2,16)

# Min distortions to be stored for the plot
meanDistortions=[]

# Silhouette scores to be stored for plotting.
silhouette_scores=[]

# Get min distortions and silhouette scores for various number of clusters.
for k in clusters:
    model = KMeans(random_state=SEED, n_clusters=k)
    prediction = model.fit_predict(scaled_df)
    mean_dist = sum(np.min(cdist(scaled_df, model.cluster_centers_, 'euclidean'), axis=1)) / scaled_df.shape[0]
    meanDistortions.append(mean_dist)
    silhouette_scores.append(silhouette_score(scaled_df, prediction))

# Elbow plot 
plt.figure(figsize=(15,8))
plt.plot(clusters, meanDistortions, 'bx-');
plt.xlabel('Num. Of. Clusters (k)')
plt.ylabel('Average distortion')
plt.title('Selecting k with the Elbow Method')
plt.show()

# Let's look at the corresponding Silhouette scores
pd.DataFrame({'Silhouette Scores': silhouette_scores}, index = clusters).plot(figsize=(15,8));
plt.xlabel('Num. Of. Clusters (k)')
plt.ylabel('Silhouette Scores')
plt.title('Silhouette scores for different clusters')
plt.show()

Observations for knee test:¶

  • There seems to be a "knee" at four clusters.
  • There also seems to be "knee" at three and seven clusters.
  • Three and four clusters have considerable Silhouette scores, but seven clusters has lower silhouette score.
  • Let's consider 3, 4 and 5 as potential number of clusters for further analysis.

Hierarchical Clustering ¶

In this section we perform Hierarchical Clustering using scipy.cluster.hierarchy. We chose the best linkage method using dendrogram and cophenetic correlation and analyze the clusters using box plots.

In [17]:
# Linkage methods to be selected
# Reference: https://docs.scipy.org/doc/scipy/reference/generated/scipy.cluster.hierarchy.linkage.html
linkage_methods = ['single', 'complete', 'average', 'weighted', 'centroid', 'median', 'ward']    

# Distance metric
dist_metric='euclidean'

# Plot index
idx=1

# Let's plot dendrograms and calculate cophenetic correlations for above linkage methods
plt.figure(figsize=(20,30))
for link in linkage_methods:
    # Perform hierarchical clustering
    Z = linkage(scaled_df, metric=dist_metric, method=link, optimal_ordering=True)
    
    # Compute the cophenetic correlation
    c, _ = cophenet(Z , pdist(scaled_df))
    
    # Let's look at the dendrogram
    plt.subplot(4, 2, idx)
    plt.title('Dendrogram for ' + link.upper() + ' linkage. Cophenetic Corr: ' + str(round(c, 3)), fontsize=14)    
    plt.xlabel('Sample Index')
    plt.ylabel('Distance')
    dendrogram(Z, p=5, truncate_mode='lastp')
    idx += 1

Observations on dendrograms and cophenetic correlation:¶

  • Average method has the highest cophenetic correlation.

  • The average method with four clusters will yield uneven segmentation with one of the groups having just one record. However, it will yield better segmentation with three clusters.

  • The ward has lower cophenetic correlation but will yield better segmentation using three and four clusters.

In [18]:
# In order to select best linkage method, Let's further look at the silhouette scores for average and ward methods

# Map of linkage method to its dedrogramic distances for 2, 3, 4 and 5 clsuters
link_dist_map = {
    'average' : [4, 3.25, 3.05, 2.75],
    'ward': [45, 30, 18, 12]
}

# Calculate Silhouette scores for above methods and number of clusters
results_dict = {}
for link, distances in link_dist_map.items():
    Z = linkage(scaled_df, metric='euclidean', method=link, optimal_ordering=True)
    for d in distances:
        clusters = fcluster(Z, t=d, criterion='distance')
        score = silhouette_score(scaled_df, clusters)
        results_dict[link + ' linkage with ' + str(max(clusters)) + ' clusters'] = round(score,3)

pd.DataFrame(results_dict, index=['Silhouette Score']).T

Observations:¶

Let's compare the clusters formed by K-Means and Hierarchical clustering.

Cluster 0 of K-Means is similar to Cluster 1 of Hierarchical: Customers in this cluster have high credit card limits (108K - 170K) and highest total number of credit cards (8-10). They have the lowest in person bank visits and highest online visits. They also have the lowest calls made. This cluster has fewer customers (50).

Cluster 1 of K-Means is similar to Cluster 3 of Hierarchical: These are the customers with lowest credit card limits (8K - 16K) and have the least number of credit cards (1-3). They also have lower in person visits to the bank and moderate online visits. However, they have the highest number of calls. This group has considerable number of customers, over 200.

Cluster 2 of K-Means is similar to Cluster 2 of Hierarchical: This is group of customers with moderate credit card limits (14K- 52K) and have considerable number of credit cards (4-6). They have the highest in person bank visits and lowest online visits. Also, they have lower phone calls to the bank. This group has highest number of customers, over 350.

Analyzing Clusters - Finding Answers to Key Questions ¶

The best average Silhouette scores from both clustering algorithms are identical. As seen in the previous section, the segmentation achieved by both algorithms is very similar.

Key Questions:¶

1. How many different segments of customers are there?

Broadly, there are three different segments of customers that can be considered.

2. How are these segments different from each other?

The three segments are different from each other in following ways:

Segment 1: Customers with high credit limits: These are also the customers with highest number of total credit cards. They rarely visit the bank in person and often visit the bank online. They rarely call bank support. They are lower in counts (about 50).

Segment 2: Customers with moderate credit limits: These are also the customers with moderate number of total credit cards. They frequently visit the bank in person and few times visit the bank online. They occasionally call the bank support.

Segment 3: Customers with low credit limits: These are also the customers with lowest number of credit cards. They visit the bank in person very less frequently but occasionally visits bank online. They call the bank support very often.

3. What are your recommendations to the bank on how to better market to and service these customers?

Segment 1 customers are fairly rich people who prefer more credit cards and also handle most of their bank related tasks online. They could be targeted online for marketing campaigns and products such as new credit cards, account upgrades, term deposits, credit card consolidations, going paperless, etc. Support service for these customers could be provided online and remotely as well, since they do not prefer visiting bank in person.

Segment 2 customers have moderate credit limits and moderate number of credit cards and prefer visiting bank in person and less online, so in person marketing campaigns would be useful. Also handling their support request in person would help. They do occasionally try to access the bank portal online, so persuading them to use the banking services online more would help in long term.

Segment 3 customers have the lowest credit limits and lower number of credit cards. They have moderate online visits. For marketing purpose they should be targeted more online. The bank can target them for additional credit cards, term deposit, etc. The bank should focus on supporting them better, as the have highest number of support calls.

In case of 4 cluster segmentation, we found a subgroup of Segment 3, where credit limits were lowest but the number of credit cards were slightly high. They also visited the bank in person frequently. Such customers should be targeted in person more for marketing campaigns and support requests. Perhaps they are potential customers for more credit cards and higher credit limits with additional along with other bank products.
